  "local_port": 54242,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I get admitted to MIT?",
  "response": "Getting admitted to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) is highly competitive, but with careful planning, dedication, and a strong application, you can maximize your chances. Here\u2019s a comprehensive guide to help you:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Excel Academically**\n- **Strong Grades**: MIT looks for students with exceptional academic performance, particularly in STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics) subjects. Aim for a high GPA, especially in challenging courses.\n- **Rigorous Coursework**: Take the most advanced classes available at your school, such as AP, IB, or honors courses. MIT values students who challenge themselves.\n- **Standardized Tests**: MIT requires the SAT or ACT (as of Fall 2023, it reinstated the SAT/ACT requirement). Aim for scores in the 99th percentile (e.g., 1550+ on the SAT or 35+ on the ACT).\n\n---\n\n### **2. Demonstrate Passion for STEM**\n- **Projects and Research**: Engage in independent projects, research, or internships related to your field of interest. MIT values students who show initiative and creativity.\n- **Competitions**: Participate in STEM competitions like the Intel Science and Engineering Fair (ISEF), Math Olympiad, or Robotics competitions. Success in these can set you apart.\n- **Extracurriculars**: Show leadership and depth in STEM-related clubs or activities, such as coding clubs, debate (for logical thinking), or engineering projects.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Develop a Well-Rounded Profile**\n- **Non-STEM Interests**: While STEM is MIT\u2019s focus, they also value students who excel in other areas like music, art, writing, or athletics.\n- **Leadership**: Take on leadership roles in clubs, organizations, or community initiatives.\n- **Community Service**: Demonstrate a commitment to making a positive impact in your community.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Craft a Compelling Application**\n- **Essays**: MIT\u2019s application includes several short essays. Be authentic, reflective, and showcase your personality, passions, and how you align with MIT\u2019s mission.\n- **Recommendations**: Request letters from teachers who know you well and can speak to your academic abilities, work ethic, and character.\n- **Interviews**: If offered, take advantage of the MIT interview to highlight your personality, interests, and fit for the institute.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Highlight Your Unique Qualities**\n- MIT looks for students who are innovative, collaborative, and driven to solve real-world problems. Showcase what makes you unique and how you\u2019ve made an impact in your community or field of interest.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Apply Strategically**\n- **Early Action**: MIT offers a non-binding Early Action option. Applying early can demonstrate your strong interest.\n- **Deadlines**: MIT\u2019s Early Action deadline is typically November 1st, and Regular Action is January 4th.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Prepare for Rejection**\nMIT\u2019s acceptance rate is extremely low (around 4%). Even highly qualified applicants may not get in, so apply to a range of schools to ensure you have options.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Stay Informed**\n- Visit MIT\u2019s admissions website for the latest requirements and tips.\n- Attend virtual or in-person admissions events to learn more about the institute and its expectations.\n\n---\n\nAdmission to MIT requires a combination of academic excellence, passion for STEM, leadership, and a unique personal story. Focus on building a strong profile and presenting yourself authentically in your application. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
